THIS IS A STORYCORPS RECORDING OF A STORY TOLD BY PROFESSOR RONALD CLARK ABOUT HIS RATHER PECULIAR CHILDHOOD HOME.
AS A CHILD, RONALD INITIALLY THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS WEALTHY, BUT HIS PARENTS TOLD HE THAT HE WAS NOT.
AT ONE POINT IN THE YOUNG BOY'S LIFE, HIS FATHER WAS OFFERED A JOB AS THE CUSTODIAN TO THE NEW YORK PUBLIC LIBRARY'S WASHINGTON HEIGHTS BRANCH.
WHEN HIS FATHER TOOK THE JOB AS THE CUSTODIAN, RONALD MOVED WITH HIS FAMILY INTO A TOP-FLOOR APARTMENT AT THE LIBRARY.
FOR A WHILE, ROBERT WAS EMBARRASSED BY HIS ATYPICAL HOME, BECAUSE, AS HE RECALLS, CHILDREN WISH TO SEEM "NORMAL" TO THEIR PEERS.
HOWEVER, THE BOY SOON GREW TO APPRECIATE HIS HOME.
HIS FATHER TOOK GREAT PRIDE IN MAINTAINING THE LIBRARY'S CLEANLINESS, WAXING THE FLOORS AND EVEN THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
AS A BOY, RONALD BEGAN TO APPRECIATE THAT HIS FATHER TOOK BETTER CARE OF HIS LIBRARY THAN OTHER CUSTODIANS DID.
THIS RESPECT FOR WHAT THE BOY WOULD LATER CALL "THE TEMPLE OF KNOWLEDGE," CLEARLY MADE AN IMPRESSION ON THE PROFESSOR-TO-BE AND HE SOON GREW TO LOVE THE LIBRARY, TOO.
ALTHOUGH HE WOULD HAVE TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAYS, AT NIGHT, HE WAS ABLE TO PLAY IN THE LIBRARY.
STILL, HIS "PLAY" TURNED TO A LOVE OF READING AND LEARNING.
WHEN HE WAS UNABLE TO SLEEP, HE WOULD READ UNTIL 3 IN THE MORNING.
HIS LOVE OF READING LED ROBERT TO DEVELOP A LIFELONG LOVE OF LEARNING.
YEARS LATER, ROBERT CLARK BECAME A COLLEGE PROFESSOR AND SHOWED HIS FATHER THE NAMEPLATE ON HIS OFFICE DOOR.

ALTHOUGH HIS FATHER DID NOT SAY MUCH, IT WAS EVIDENT TO THE PROFESSOR THAT HIS SUCCESS AS AN ACADEMIC MEANT A GREAT DEAL TO HIS FATHER, WHO HAD WANTED HIS SON TO DO BETTER IN LIFE THAN HE HAD DONE AS A CUSTODIAN.
ROBERT CLARK TELLS THE STORY OF HIS UNCONVENTIONAL CHILDHOOD LIVING QUARTERS TO STORYCORPS.
AS A YOUNG BOY, CLARK RECALLS, HE THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS WEALTHY.
HE WAS SURPRISED WHEN HE WAS TOLD THAT HIS FAMILY WAS, IN FACT, POOR.
THE NEXT THING HE REMEMBERS IS HIS FATHER BEING OFFERED A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN IN THE NEW YORK PUBLIC LIBRARY'S BRANCH IN WASHINGTON HEIGHTS.
WHEN HIS FATHER TOOK THE JOB, ROBERT MOVED WITH HIS PARENTS INTO A TOP-FLOOR APARTMENT IN THE LIBRARY.
AS A CHILD, ROBERT WAS EMBARRASSED BY HIS UNCONVENTIONAL LIVING QUARTERS AND DID NOT INVITE HIS PEERS OVER.
HOWEVER, DESPITE HIS EMBARRASSMENT, ROBERT CAME TO APPRECIATE A GOOD DEAL ABOUT LIVING IN THE LIBRARY.
HIS FATHER WAS A HARD-WORKING MAN WHO TOOK GREAT PRIDE IN MAINTAINING AN IMPECCABLY CLEAN LIBRARY, WHICH ROBERT RECALLS FONDLY AS THE "TEMPLE OF KNOWLEDGE.
HIS FATHER WOULD NOT ONLY WAX THE FLOORS OF THE LIBRARY, HE WOULD ALSO WAX THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
WHEREAS OTHER LIBRARIES WOULD HAVE GARBAGE ON THE FLOORS SUCH AS GUM WRAPPERS, THE WASHINGTON HEIGHTS BRANCH LIBRARY WAS VERY CLEAN.
ROBERT RECALLS THAT HE WOULD HAVE TO BE QUIET IN THE LIBRARY DURING THE DAY, BUT THAT HE WOULD HAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO PLAY--EVEN LOUDLY--IN THE LIBRARY AT NIGHT.
ULTIMATELY, THOUGH, HE WAS DRAWN TO READING AND SPENT MANY HOURS READING THE BOOKS WITH WHICH HE WAS SURROUNDED.
WHEN HE COULDN'T SLEEP AT NIGHT, HE WOULD READ.
SOMETIMES HE WOULD STAY UP READING UNTIL THREE IN THE MORNING.
HE CREDITS THIS UPBRINGING WITH FOSTERING HIS LIFELONG LOVE OF LEARNING.
AS A PROFESSOR, ROBERT CLARK INVITED HIS FATHER TO HIS OFFICE, WHERE THE ELDER CLARK QUIETLY REGARDED HIS SON'S ACADEMIC SUCCESS.

ALTHOUGH HE DID NOT SAY MUCH, ROBERT'S FATHER DID APPEAR TO BE QUITE TOUCHED AND ROBERT BELIEVES IT WAS BECAUSE HE HAD ACHIEVED WHAT HIS FATHER HAD ALWAYS WANTED FOR HIM: A BETTER LIFE THAN HIS PARENTS HAD HAD.
